<section class="section section--alt" id="qb-help-duplicate-transactions-definition">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">In plain terms</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">&ldquo;Duplicate transactions,&rdquo; plainly.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>A duplicate transaction is the same real transaction recorded in QuickBooks more than once &mdash; the same deposit, check, expense, or transfer showing up twice (or more). It usually isn&rsquo;t two different events; it&rsquo;s one event captured twice, most often because the bank feed delivered it once and something else &mdash; a manual entry, a second connection, a repeat import &mdash; captured it again. The effect is that your income or expenses look bigger than they are, your reports are wrong, and reconciliation breaks because the register total no longer matches the bank.</p>
      <p>The good news is that most duplicates trace to a short list of causes, and the self-fix steps below address them in order of likelihood &mdash; identifying the doubled entries and carefully removing the duplicate copy clears a large share of cases. The one thing the steps can&rsquo;t undo is a mistake: <em>deleting transactions is irreversible</em>, so the first step is always a backup, and the work to do it safely &mdash; keeping the correct copy, not breaking a closed reconciliation, not disturbing figures that fed a tax return &mdash; is where it stops being a quick delete and becomes a ProAdvisor job. And if the underlying issue is your Intuit account or login, that&rsquo;s Intuit&rsquo;s to resolve &mdash; not something we can reach.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

